# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ac-power-plugs-and-sockets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] An **acorn tube**, or **acorn valve**, is any member of a family of VHF/UHF vacuum tubes starting just before World War II.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] They were named after their resemblance to the acorn, specifically due to the glass cap at one end of the tube that looked similar to the cap on an acorn.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The acorn tubes found widespread use in radios and radar systems.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] High-frequency performance is limited by (1) parasitic lead inductance and capacitance and skin effect, and (2) electron transit time (the time required to travel from cathode to anode).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] Transit time effects are complicated, but one simple effect is the phase margin; another one is input conductance, also known as grid loading.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] At extremely high frequencies, electrons arriving at the grid may become out of phase with those departing towards the anode.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] This imbalance of charge causes the grid to exhibit a reactance that is much less than its low-frequency "open circuit" characteristic.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] Acorn- as well as Lighthouse tubes and Nuvistors attempt to minimize this effect by arranging cathode, grid(s) and anode as closely spaced together as possible.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The original range included about half a dozen tubes, designed to work in the VHF range.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The 954 and 956 types are sharp and remote cut-off pentodes, respectively, all with indirect 6.3 V, 150 mA heaters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] Types 957, 958 and 959 are for portable equipment and have 1.25 V NiCd battery heaters.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The 957 is a medium-μ signal triode, the 958 is a transmitting triode with dual, paralleled filaments for increased emission, and the 959 is a sharp cut-off pentode like the 954.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The 957 and 959 draw 50 mA heater current, the 958 twice as much.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] In 1942, the 958A with tightened emission specifications was introduced after it turned out that 958s with excessively high emission kept working after the filament power was turned off, the filament still sufficiently heating on the anode current alone.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] After the introduction of the miniature 7-pin base, the 954, 955 and 956 were made available with this base as 9001, 9002 and 9003.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] Larger, higher-power types such as the 316A, 368A, 388A, and 703A triodes and the 713A and 717A pentodes were referred to as *Doorknob* tubes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/acorn-tube] The introduction of the EF50 was the first serious competition for the acorn design, and replaced the acorns in many roles, especially post-war when millions of surplus EF50s were dumped on the market.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] An **adapter** or **adaptor** is a device that converts attributes of one electrical device or system to those of an otherwise incompatible device or system.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Some modify power or signal attributes, while others merely adapt the physical form of one connector to another.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Many countries with ties to Europe use 230-volt, 50 Hz AC mains electricity, using a variety of power plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Difficulty arises when moving an electrical device between countries that use different sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] A passive electric power adapter, sometimes called a *travel plug* or *travel adapter*, allows using a plug from one region with a foreign socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] As other countries supply 120-volt, 60 Hz AC, using a travel adapter in a country with a different supply poses a safety hazard if the connected device does not support both input voltages.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] An AC-to-DC power supply adapts electricity from household mains voltage (either 120 or 230 volts AC) to low-voltage DC suitable for powering consumer electronics.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Small, detached power supplies for consumer electronics are called *AC adapters*, or variously *power bricks*, *wall warts*, or *chargers*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] A *host controller* connects a computer to a peripheral device, such as a storage device, network, or human interface device.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] As a host controller can also be viewed as bridging the protocols used on the buses between peripheral and computer, and internally to the computer, it is also called a *host bus adapter*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Likewise, specific types may be called adapters: a network interface controller may be called a *network adapter*, and a graphics card a *display adapter*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Adapters (often in the form of *dongles*) allow connecting a peripheral device with one plug to a different jack on the computer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] They are often used to connect modern devices to a legacy port on an old system, or old devices to a modern port.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Such adapters may be entirely passive, or contain active circuitry.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] One kind of serial port adapter enables connections between 25-contact and nine-contact connectors, but does not affect electrical power- and signalling-related attributes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] HDMI is backward compatible with the single-channel digital video interface (DVI-D or DVI-I, but not DVI-A or dual-channel DVI).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] When using an adapter or an asymmetric cable, no signal conversion is required, so video quality is not lost. “This means that DVI can be connected to an HDMI input using an adapter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] DVI was an important step forward, introducing digital video.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] A separate cable to the audio output on the computer or sound card was required for that.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Any DVI-HDMI adapter can function as an HDMI-DVI adapter (and vice versa).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Usually, the only limitation is the gender of the adapter connectors, as well as the gender of cables and connectors with which it is used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Features characteristic of HDMI, such as remote control and audio transmission, are not available on devices using the legacy DVI-D signal.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] However, many devices output HDMI via a DVI connector (for example, ATI 3000 series and NVIDIA GTX 200 graphics cards), and some multimedia displays can accept HDMI (including audio) through a DVI input.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] The exact capabilities beyond basic compatibility may vary.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Adapters and active converters are also available for connecting HDMI to other video interfaces, including older analog formats as well as digital formats such as DisplayPort.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Introduced in the 2000s, DisplayPort was designed to replace older standards such as VGA, DVI, and FPD-Link.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] Although it is not directly compatible with these formats, adapters are available for connecting to HDMI, DVI, VGA, and other interfaces.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] There are USB-CEC adapters that allow a computer to control devices supporting Consumer Electronics Control.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/adaptors] In software, an adapter is a piece of code that complies with an interface of an existing component while actually using another implementation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/additron-tube] The **Additron** was an electron tube designed by Dr.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/additron-tube] Josef Kates, circa 1950, to replace the several individual electron tubes and support components required to perform the function of a single bit digital full adder.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/additron-tube] The Additron neither went into production at the Canadian Rogers Vacuum Tube Company, where the prototypes were built, nor was it used in the UTEC machine.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/additron-tube] It did make a widely publicized appearance at the 1950 Canadian National Exhibition operating an electronic game of Tic-Tac-Toe, dubbed *Bertie the Brain*, to show the marvels of electronic computing.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/additron-tube] The tube was registered with the Radio Television Manufacturing Association on 20 March 1951 as type 6047.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The germanium **alloy-junction transistor**, or **alloy transistor**, was an early type of bipolar junction transistor, developed at General Electric and RCA in 1951 as an improvement over the earlier grown-junction transistor.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The usual construction of an alloy-junction transistor is a germanium crystal forming the base, with emitter and collector alloy beads fused on opposite sides.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] Indium and antimony were commonly used to form the alloy junctions on a bar of N-type germanium.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The collector junction pellet would be about 50 mils (thousandths of an inch) in diameter, and the emitter pellet about 20 mils.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The base region would be on the order of 1 mil (0.001 inches, 25 μm) thick.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] There were several types of improved alloy-junction transistors developed over the years that they were manufactured.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] All types of alloy-junction transistors became obsolete in the early 1960s, with the introduction of the planar transistor which could be mass-produced easily while alloy-junction transistors had to be made individually.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The first germanium planar transistors had much worse characteristics than alloy-junction germanium transistors of the period, but they cost much less, and the characteristics of planar transistors improved very rapidly, quickly exceeding those of all earlier germanium transistors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy transistor** (**MAT**) was developed by Philco as an improved type of alloy-junction transistor, it offered much higher speed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] It is constructed of a semiconductor crystal forming the base, into which a pair of wells are etched (similar to Philco's earlier surface-barrier transistor) on opposite sides then fusing emitter and collector alloy beads into the wells.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy diffused transistor** (**MADT**), or **micro-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philco as an improved type of micro-alloy transistor; it offered even higher speed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] It is a type of diffused-base transistor.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] Before using electrochemical techniques and etching depression wells into the base semiconductor crystal material, a heated diffused phosphorus gaseous layer is created over the entire intrinsic semiconductor base crystal, creating a N-type graded base semiconductor material.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The emitter well is etched very shallow into this diffused base layer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] For high-speed operation, the collector well is etched all the way through the diffused base layer and through most of the intrinsic base semiconductor region, forming an extremely thin base region.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] A doping-engineered electric field was created in the diffused base layer to reduce the charge carrier base transit time (similar to the drift-field transistor).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The **post-alloy diffused transistor** (**PADT**), or **post-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philips (but GE and RCA filed for patent and Jacques Pankove of RCA received patent for it) as an improvement to the germanium alloy-junction transistor, it offered even higher speed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The Philco micro-alloy diffused transistor had a mechanical weakness that ultimately limited their speed; the thin diffused base layer would break if made too thin, but to get high speed it needed to be as thin as possible.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] Also it was very hard to control alloying on both sides of such a thin layer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The post-alloy diffused transistor solved this problem by making the bulk semiconductor crystal the collector (instead of the base), which could be as thick as necessary for mechanical strength.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The diffused base layer was created on top of this.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] Then two alloy beads, one P-type and one N-type were fused on top of the diffused base layer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alloy-junction-transistor] The bead having the same type as the base dopant then became part of the base and the bead having the opposite type from the base dopant became the emitter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Australasian standard three-pin plug, with part insulation on the Active/Line and Neutral pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The plug consists of two flat pins forming an inverted V-shape, and a vertical earthing pin below with a slightly longer length.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Double insulated appliances may omit the earth pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] When viewing a plug from its face (Earth facing downwards), the top left prong is Neutral and the top right is Active (Live/Phase).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In accordance with AS/NZS 3112:2000, all plugs sold since 2004 are required to have insulation halfway down their Active and Neutral prongs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Since 2000, the nominal voltage in most areas of Australia has been 230 V; the transition was complete by 2022.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Fiji, Tonga and Papua New Guinea remains at a nominal 240 V, and in the Solomon Islands it is 220 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The standards of China and Argentina also use the Type I plug and socket, though the Live (Active) and Neutral pins are swapped in Argentina, and neither includes insulation on these prongs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In both countries the voltage is 220 V, and the outlets are sometimes mounted upside-down with the earth pin at the top for safety.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Differences in voltage/polarity may give rise to compatibility issues, especially for travellers and those purchasing appliances overseas or online.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Most 230 V equipment will work with a supply voltage in the range 220–240 V without issues.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The mains frequency is 50 Hz in all these countries.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The Australian standard of 1937 was the result of a "gentlemen's agreement", reportedly from 1930, between manufacturers Fred Cook of Ring-Grip, Geoffrey Gerard of Gerard Industries and Brian Harper Miller of the State Electricity Commission of Victoria (SECV).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The design was based on an American plug and socket-outlet first intended for use at 120 V which was patented in 1916 under U.S. patent 1,179,728 by Harvey Hubbell.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] By the early 1930s this design had been up-rated to 250 V 10 A capacity and Hubbell had supplied the Australian electrical industry with his sockets.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Current Australian plugs fit these American outlets perfectly.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] (While this socket-outlet never became a NEMA standard design, the 50 A NEMA 10-50R, has a similar pin configuration in a larger form.) Argentina, Uruguay, and China based their plugs and sockets on the same design.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] New Zealand also adopted the Australian design, since Australian equipment and many electrical appliances were exported to that country.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] One of the reasons behind the adoption of that particular design was that it was cheap to make, with the flat pins being able to be easily stamped out of sheet brass, in contrast to round pins or thicker rectangular ones used in other countries.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] This was also a consideration when the Chinese authorities officially adopted the design in relatively recent times, despite the considerable inroads the British plug had made, because of its use in Hong Kong.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The Chinese socket is normally mounted with the earth pin at the top.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] This is considered to offer some protection should a conductive object fall between the plug and the socket.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In Australia, the C112 standard was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] A major update was released in 2000 as AS/NZS 3112:2000, which mandated active and neutral insulated pins on the plugs sold for use with these socket-outlets after 3 April 2005.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The standard AS/NZS 3112:2004 introduced more stringent testing procedures to test for bending of the pins and subtle changes to the radius of the pin tips.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The current version is AS/NZS 3112:2017.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] AS/NZS 3112 compliant plugs have two flat pins forming an inverted V-shape plus a vertical earthing pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The flat blades measure 6.35 by 1.6 mm (1⁄4 by 1⁄16 in) with the active (line) and neutral pins 17.35 mm (11⁄16 in) long set 30° to the vertical and the vertical earth pin being 20 mm (0.787 in) in length.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The pins are arranged at 120° angles around a common midpoint, with the active and neutral centred 7.92 mm (5⁄16 in) from the midpoint, and the earth pin centred 10.31 mm (3⁄8 in) away.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] A standard socket-outlet provides a nominal RMS voltage of 230 volts at a maximum of 10 amps and always includes an earth connection.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] "Shuttered" socket-outlets are available, but these are not required by regulation.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] There are unearthed versions of the plug used with this outlet having only the two flat inverted V-aligned pins, without the earthing pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Such plugs are only to be used for devices where other safety standards are in use (e.g. double insulation).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] They are not available separately but only integrally with power cords specifically designed for the purpose.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] A view of the wiring side of a typical dual socket-outlet is also shown on the right, together with an annotated view of the mechanism, without the front cover.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] If required, such dual socket-outlets can be obtained (at additional cost) using insulation displacement as a means of connecting to the supply conductors, as can be seen in the illustration – below.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The benefits claimed for their use in these applications include up to 50% faster installation, due to the reduction in the stripping, twisting and screwing down processes.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] However, "stationary appliances" (such as fans) and most "luminaires" may be controlled by a remote switch, which would switch the supply via the socket-outlet concerned.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Exceptions could be devices such as illuminated "Exit" signs, which require connection to the power supply at all times.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Standard single phase 230 V domestic socket outlets in Australia and New Zealand are rated at 10 A.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] From this it may be seen that any plug can be inserted into a socket outlet of the same or higher rating but cannot be inserted into a socket outlet of lower rating.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Hence, a 10 A plug will fit into all of the five types of socket outlets, a 15 A plug will fit into all except a 10 A (and so on) while a 32 A plug will fit only into a 32 A socket outlet.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Higher rated socket outlets are sometimes used for connection of electric ovens in domestic kitchens.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] These sockets are rarely seen in industrial environments, where AS/NZS 3123 weather-proof sockets are generally preferred.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] A variant of the Australian standard 10 amperes plug has a socket on the back to allow connection of a second appliance to the same outlet.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] This type of plug is known officially as a "socket adapter plug" but is referred to colloquially, in Australia, as a "piggy-back plug", or in New Zealand, as a "tap-on" plug and is shown below.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In Australia the plug is now available only as part of a pre-assembled extension cord, or by special order.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In New Zealand, re-wireable PDL 940 "tap-on" plugs are more widely available.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Other variants include plug/sockets with a rating of 10 A using a round earth pin, which is used on "special use" circuits, such as storage heaters in classrooms; and a 110 V 10 A version that has round active & neutral pins with a flat earth pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The latter is rated at only 110 V (since certain [foreign] 110 V plugs could be inserted into the socket-outlet) and may be used on PAR 64 lights, where two 110 volt 1000 watt lamps are used in series.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The active terminal is the first 'socket' from the earth 'socket' in a clockwise direction when viewing the front of a socket-outlet.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Care should be taken if Argentinian standards or faulty wiring swaps the active and neutral pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Care should also be taken with the 10 A version with the round pin as physically compatible, but electrically incompatible NEMA 7–15 connector used for 277 V 15 A connections is encountered in commercial or industrial settings in the Americas.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] While never "codified", since the 1960s it has become "normal" for socket-outlets manufactured for use in Australia/New Zealand to have the earth pin facing downwards, so that the longer earth pin will be the last to lose contact if the inserted plug is tugged downwards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Many products such as "side-entry" plugs (with the cord exit in the 5 o'clock/135-degree position) and extra low voltage "plug packs" are manufactured for use in Australia/New Zealand assuming that the socket into which they will be inserted has the earth pin downwards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In 1980, the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) rationalised the 220 V and 240 V nominal voltage levels around the world to a consistent 230 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] This rationalisation was ostensibly made to improve the economics of making appliances by allowing manufacturers to produce a range of items with a rated voltage of 230 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Not all countries have yet converted to the new standard.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The nominal voltage in most areas of Australia had been set at 240 V in 1926.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In 2000, Standards Australia issued a system Standard AS60038, with 230 V as the nominal voltage with a +10% to −6% variation at the point of supply, i.e., 253 V to 216.2 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] A new power quality standard, AS 61000.3.100, was released in 2011 that details additional requirements.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The new standard stipulates a nominal 230 V, and the *allowable* voltage to the customer's point of supply is, as mentioned, +10% to −6%.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] However, the *preferred* operating range is +6% to −2%.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In Australia, the actual voltages delivered to customers is set at the state/territory level.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] As of 2022, all states/territories (excluding Western Australia, which remains at 240 V) have transitioned to 230 V standards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Queensland began the transition to 230 V in 2017.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The reason given for Queensland's decision to move was the increased use of grid-tied rooftop solar installations raising the grid voltage.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] By lowering the voltage to 230 V, additional headroom of 960 megawatts was created to accommodate future residential power generation from rooftop solar.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The voltage in Fiji, Tonga, and Papua New Guinea is still 240 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In China, the Solomon Islands, and Argentina the voltage is 220 V.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The Chinese CPCS-CCC (Chinese 10 A/250 V) plugs and socket-outlets are almost identical, differing by only 1 mm (0.039 in) longer pins and installed "upside down".
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] These are the standard in Mainland China.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] AS 3112 plugs will physically connect with Chinese sockets, although they may not be electrically compatible to the Chinese 220 V standards.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The reverse case is not true as Chinese plugs usually cannot fit AS 3112 sockets due to its thinner and shorter prongs causing it to fall out.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Originally there was no convention as to the direction of the earth pin.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] Often it was facing upwards, as socket-outlets in China now do but it could also be downwards or horizontal, in either direction.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] There are also 16 A and 20 A variants with bigger pins.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] These plugs are different from the Australian 15 A and 20 A plugs.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] In parallel, the GB 1002 standard also defines the Type A or NEMA-1 connector (for non-earthed appliances up to 10 amps).
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The Argentinian plugs and socket-outlets are also identical to the Australian AS 3112, but the polarity is reversed and the pins are one millimetre longer.
[src:ac-power-plugs-and-sockets/as-nzs-3112] The plugs are also used in some places in Uruguay albeit less common than Type L and Schuko.
